    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-03-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-03-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1206"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1206">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.512/223.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Hostetter</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 637.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate.</hi>
                            <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Hermosillo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-03-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 17, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    the Department’s telegram March 16, regarding the collection of mining taxes by
                    the Constitutionalists after having once been paid to the Federals. I had same
                    complaint upon the return of General Carranza from Sinaloa and he, at the time,
                    promised to look into the matter, although he held he had a right to demand the
                    payment of the same. I told him according and agreeable to international law, it
                    was not right to demand this payment, as a government in power had a right to
                    collect these same taxes. It is possible, that on account of his constant
                    moving, he forgot to look into the matter. I have wired to Juarez in regard to
                    the matter.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Louis Hostetter</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
